the cultural politics of chocolate in latin america center for latin american studies jump to navigation stanford university center for latin american studies search this site home events the cultural politics of chocolate in latin america the cultural politics of chocolate in latin america tuesday september 27 2011 12 15pm 1 05pm in his talk professor hector hoyos from the department of iberian and latin american cultures compares the role of chocolate in the work of the brazilian new york based artist vik muniz with the role of cacao in diego de rivera's murals by extrapolating the notion of transculturation originally conceived by the cuban anthropologist fernando ortiz in his reflections on sugar and tobacco hoyos analyzes muniz's cosmopolitan use of chocolate vis a vis rivera's autochthonous vindication of cacao hoyos's current research focuses on representations of globalization in post 1989 latin american fiction his articles have appeared or are forthcoming in several edited collections as well as in the journals chasqui revista de estudios hispanicos comparative literature studies journal of latin american cultural studies revista de estudios sociales and revista iberoamericana among others he is working on two book manuscripts entitled beyond bolano the global latin american novel and el deber de la travesura cesar aira y la critica cultural hector hoyos assistant professor iberian and latin american cultures stanford university bolivar house 582 alvarado row attachment size hoyos jpg 529.12 kb last updated january 25 2012 10 58am calendar main menu about degree programs visiting faculty & scholar programs grants & fellowships people events newsletter giving to clas secondary menu stanford home ica clasp login contact stanford university center for latin american studies bolivar house 582 alvarado row stanford ca 94305 usa phone 650.723 4444 fax 650.723 9822 stanford university terms of use copyright complaints
